\begin_layout BeginFrame
Admission requirements - the hard facts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
rule
\series default
: You must have passed (grade A-E) every compulsory course within the study
 program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
exception
\series default
: You may have a course moment (exam, lab, project) left to fulfil from
 one course.
 This moment shall be completed at latest in March 2013.
 If not, your thesis project will be halted and postponed to next term!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
This year's exception
\series default
: You may start the master thesis course if you can realistically argue
 that you will have passed every compulsory course by March 2013.
 If you are not done by March, your thesis project will be halted and postponed
 to next term!
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
A master thesis is a course
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Successive deadlines and compulsory moments: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thesis proposal seminar 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mid-term report 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Revision meeting 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Defence seminar
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Omission to adhere to these moments may lead to that the examination of
 your work will be postponed to next term!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Supervisors and examiners have been appointed to that term in which you
 are supposed to complete your work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You shall act as opponent on another thesis and that should be done according
 to the schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Part 1 - Problem formulation and literature review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Time frame: Now- Feb 11 (Project Proposal Seminar).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Make a careful review of the 
\series bold
background
\series default
 to your problem, 
\series bold
available data
\series default
 and the 
\series bold
specific questions 
\series default
put by the commissioner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Put your work in a scientific context
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Has anyone studied your kind of problem previously? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Are there studies of similar problems? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What lessons can be learnt? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What is new in your study?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Why
\series default
 did you choose a certain model/method/algorithm?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Google! Google! Google!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Write a first draft of background, your preliminary objective, description
 of data and literature review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prepare for your 
\series bold
Thesis Proposal Seminar
\series default
 (oral with slides).
 This shall include suggestions of methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Part 2 - Main work, first phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Time frame: Feb 12 - March 25 (Mid-term Report Seminar).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Amend your thesis proposal taking aspects from the proposal seminar into
 account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Work with your project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Adhere to regular supervision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Write draft pages containing results and analysis of these 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Towards the end of the period, prepare for the Mid-term report seminar:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Short written summary of your progress so far 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Oral presentation with slides
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Part 3 - Main work, second phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Time frame
\series default
: March 16 - May 13.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take aspects from the mid-term report seminar into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prepare the skeleton of your final theses and include the parts that are
 already written.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finalize your analyses and complete the results part of your thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finalize the methodology chapter and the reference list of your thesis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Put strong effort on writing a good discussion part.
 It should comprise several pages.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Formulate your conclusions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Write a summary (max.
 1 page) of your thesis and provide a title.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prepare the final manuscript to the Revision meeting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Part 4 - Finalizing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Time frame: May 14 – June 17.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Review the thesis for which you have been appointed as opponent.
 Prepare for the Revision meeting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Revision meeting is a closed seminar, where the author (respondent),
 the opponent, the supervisor and possibly another teacher take part.
 The purpose of the meeting is to go through everything in the manuscript
 that is objected to criticism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Part from the discussion made, the opponent shall provide the respondent
 with a written list of major issues and a written list of language errors
 (alternatively a version of the thesis where the language errors have been
 marked) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Part 4 - Finalizing, cont
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Make revisions in your own thesis according to what has been taken up by
 your opponent (and your supervisor) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prepare your final manuscript for the Defence seminar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prepare a good presentation for the Defence seminar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Check the revisions made in the thesis on which you are the opponent.
 Prepare discussion points for the Defence seminar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perform on the Defence seminar both as presenter and as opponent! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the discussion of your thesis during the Defence seminar and revise
 your manuscript accordingly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Submit your very final manuscript in which you have included:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
library sheet URL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
copyright page from LiU Electronic Press
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Schedule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
January 21, 2014 (Today): Course start.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
February 11, 2014: Thesis proposal seminars
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each student presents their thesis topic (including data description suggested
 methods) and outline for the work.
 20 minutes per thesis including questions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expected outcome: Each course attendant and tutor should have been informed
 about and understood the objectives of the thesis projects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compulsory to attend!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Mid-term report
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
March 25, 2014.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each student presents their progress so far.
 25 minutes per thesis including questions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A two-pages written summary of the progress should accompany the presentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expected outcome: Each course attendant and tutor should have been informed
 about what has been done so far and what is left to do for each thesis
 project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compulsory to attend! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Revision meeting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May 13, 2014: Deadline for submitting manuscript to opponent and supervisor
 in front of revision meeting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May 20-21, 2014: Revision meetings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The opponent has one week (from May 13 until May 20) to read the manuscript
 and prepare an oral and written review.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The scheduling of the meeting is made in agreement between the author, opponent
 and supervisor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Submission of final manuscript and final defense
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May 27, 2014 at 12.00: Deadline for manuscript submission
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The manuscript should be sent to the opponent and to all supervisors (Anders
 N, Mattias, Patrik, Bertil and Linda).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
June 3, 2014 (full day): Defence seminar
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each student presents their thesis for a maximum of 25 minutes, followed
 by the opposition (max.
 25 minutes) and a general discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After the seminar (or in breaks) each supervisor should summarize for the
 student what is left to be adjusted in the manuscript.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compulsory to attend the whole seminar! 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
June 17, 2014: Deadline for submission of revised manuscript
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Supervision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
normal
\series default
 frequency of meetings with the supervisor is every second week.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is mainly the student who puts “the agenda” for the meeting, i.e.
 you are expected to have some progress to show and to have prepared questions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At each meeting it is wise to agree on what are the next steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You are expected to successively show progress in your report writing:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start writing very early! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Submit manuscript parts to the supervisor in due time before the meeting
 (to facilitate feed-back)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Grading
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The grading is based on:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
scientific
\series default
 
\series bold
quality
\series default
 of the thesis (adequacy and originality of the methods used, significance
 of obtained results, discourse skill) n.b.
 “originality” is not equivalent to the development of new methods, rather
 that the methods used have not previously been applied on the kind of data
 used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Technical
\series default
 
\series bold
quality
\series default
 of the thesis (correctness of language and scientific terminology, implementati
on, quality of illustrations).
 This applies to the version of the manuscript submitted before the revision
 meeting and to the revisions made upon that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
degree
\series default
 
\series bold
of independence
\series default
.
 The supervisor gives an assessment to the examiner regarding the independence
 of the student during the master thesis.
 Listen to the supervisors advice, but do take own initiatives! (but always
 check with supervisor).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Quality of the performed opposition
\series default
, both at the revision meeting and at the final defense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Quality of presentation and communication
\series default
 (clarity of written presentation, ability to orally present, discuss and
 defend the thesis).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Supervisor and examiners
\end_layout

